<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910404-0083</DOCNO><DOCID>910404-0083.</DOCID><HL>   REVIEW andamp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides:   The Legal Skids</HL><DATE>04/04/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14</SO><CO>   GT</CO><IN>AUTO PARTS AND EQUIPMENT INCLUDING TIRES (AUP)CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)</IN><RE>OHIO (OH)</RE><LP>   Ortho-toluidine and aniline aren't household words alongthe lines of asbestos and Agent Orange, but it could be justa matter of time. These chemicals are required to makeautomobile tires, but according to a study by the Departmentof Health and Human Services, they are now to be identifiedas a health hazard for humans as well as lab animals.Researchers linked the chemicals to bladder cancer in a studyat a Goodyear Tire andamp; Rubber plant. As a result, some 2,000dye, rubber, pharmaceutical and pesticide plants could beinvolved. Goodyear complied with federal guidelines fordangerous chemicals, but there are already signs that theliability lawyers are circling overhead and may soon descendto sue the industry back to the wooden-wheel era.</LP><TEXT/></DOC>